{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01RW79J23vi2dXejo5gC1Zjk","type":"tool_result","content":"File created successfully at: /Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/tools/title-loop/input/Butternut Squash Pasta.generated.21.txt"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"34d40c09-863c-409f-994a-593ba34b4bf7","uuid":"a2702994-db79-48ca-a19b-9d76d6e88949","tool_use_result":{"type":"create","filePath":"/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/tools/title-loop/input/Butternut Squash Pasta.generated.21.txt","content":"BUTTERNUT\nSQUASH\nPASTA\n\nServes 4-5 | Preparation 25 min | Cooking 40 min\n\nIngredients:\n\nFor the pasta:\n400 grams fresh egg pasta (fettuccine or pappardelle)\n4 liters water for cooking\n2 teaspoons salt\n\nFor the sauce:\n1 large butternut squash (about 1.2 kg)\n4 tablespoons butter\n1 medium onion, finely chopped\n3 cloves garlic, minced\n150 ml heavy cream\n100 grams Parmesan cheese, grated\n1/2 teaspoon freshly grated nutmeg\n2 tablespoons sage, fresh or dried\nSalt and white pepper\n50 grams pine nuts, toasted (optional)\n\nInstructions:\n\n1. Peel and seed the butternut squash. Cut into small cubes and\nroast in a 200°C oven for 25-30 minutes until very soft and caramelized.\n\n2. While the squash roasts, bring salted water to a boil for the\npasta. Cook the pasta according to package directions until al dente.\nReserve 200 ml of pasta water before draining.\n\n3. In a large saucepan, melt butter over medium heat. Sauté the\nonion until soft and golden, about 5 minutes. Add garlic and cook\nfor 1 minute more.\n\n4. Add the roasted squash cubes to the pan. If using fresh sage,\nadd it now. Mash the squash roughly with a wooden spoon, creating\na chunky sauce. Stir in the heavy cream and Parmesan cheese.\n\n5. Season with nutmeg, salt, and pepper. If the sauce is too thick,\nthin with reserved pasta water until you reach desired consistency.\n\n6. Toss the cooked pasta with the sauce. Serve in warmed bowls,\ntopped with toasted pine nuts if desired.\n\nWine Pairing: A crisp Pinot Grigio or Vermentino works beautifully.\n","structuredPatch":[],"originalFile":null}}
